# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-justice-party
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The **2007 New South Wales state election** was held on Saturday, 24 March 2007.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The entire Legislative Assembly and half of the Legislative Council was up for election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Labor Party led by Morris Iemma won a fourth four-year term against the Liberal–National coalition led by Peter Debnam.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor's majority survived the election almost intact going from a 13 seat majority prior to the election to a marginally decreased 11 seat majority.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberals succeeded in taking two independent-held seats and one Labor-held seat, whilst the Nationals and an independent each took one Labor-held seat.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] This would be NSW Labor's last state election win until 2023.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] It also remains the most recent contest in which NSW Labor formed a majority government.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The media concluded that the choice facing voters was in finding the lesser of two evils: the three major newspapers sold in New South Wales endorsed Debnam, though not without criticising his ineptitude on the campaign trail.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The result was widely perceived as a foregone conclusion, with opposition leader Peter Debnam conceding as much the week before the poll.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Opinion polls consistently put Labor ahead in terms of voting intention and preferred premier.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The ALP would eventually lose government at the next election in a landslide defeat in 2011.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] There has been a view that the party would have suffered a less worse defeat if it had lost government at the 2007 election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The New South Wales Legislative Assembly has 93 members elected for four-year terms using instant-runoff voting, a form of preferential voting.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The voting system is the same as for the Australian House of Representatives except that New South Wales has *optional preferential voting*.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] This means that while voters may number every candidate if they wish, their vote is still formal if they choose not to.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] They may vote for one candidate only, or for as many candidates as they choose, provided that they number them in correct sequence.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The New South Wales Legislative Council has 42 members who serve eight year terms, one-half of the body being elected every four years.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Council uses the Single Transferable Vote method, a form of preferential voting for use with proportional representation.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] As for the Assembly, the numbering of preferences is optional.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] After each election, the Governor of New South Wales, appoints a member of the Legislative Assembly to the position of Premier of New South Wales.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] By convention, the party leader with the largest bloc of votes in the Assembly, is chosen.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Government is formed in the Legislative Assembly, the lower house of Parliament.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The seats for this election resulted from the boundary redistribution conducted in 2004, which did not change the number of seats notionally held by each party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] A majority being 47 seats, the Labor Party had to lose eight seats (a uniform swing of 8.7%) to lose its majority, and the Liberal–National coalition had to gain 16 seats to gain a majority.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Had the Liberal–National coalition gained at least one seat from an Independent, a uniform swing of 11.6% would have been sufficient.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Otherwise, the necessary uniform swing required would have been 12.3%.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Swings of this size are rare in New South Wales politics.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The swings required for the opposing party to take each of the Assembly's 93 seats are often illustrated by means of a Mackerras pendulum.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The following seats were described as marginal (i.e. those with a two-candidate preferred margin of 6% or less) by psephologists Malcolm Mackerras and Antony Green after the 2005 redistribution.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Legislative Council, elected by proportional representation, operates as a house of review in the New South Wales parliament.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] It is rare for parties or coalitions to secure a majority in this house.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The count was completed and results for the Legislative Council declared on 10 April.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberal and National parties ran a joint Legislative Council ticket, winning 5 seats for the Liberals and 3 seats for the Nationals and bringing the parties' totals to 10 and 5 respectively.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Electoral changes made after the 1999 election, which saw seats go to so-called microparties through elaborate preference deals, meant that both the major party groups made gains in the 2007 election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Labor Party with 39.1% of the vote gained 1 seat, to win 9, whilst the Liberal and National Parties with 34.2% gained 1 seat each to make a combined gain of 2, thereby winning 8 seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The effect of this outcome is that Labor now holds 19 out of 42 council seats, just 3 short of a majority, whilst the Coalition holds 15 seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Greens achieved a primary vote of 9.1%, an increase from their result in the 2003 election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] This has allowed them to win 2 seats (1 additional seat), bringing their total to 4 seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] This result appears to put them in a favourable position, in which they can exercise the parliamentary balance of power, and potentially provide the Labor government with the necessary majority to get legislation through the upper chamber of Parliament.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Fred Nile's Christian Democratic Party (CDP) achieved 4.4% of the vote (↑1.4%), allowing Nile to retain his seat, and keeping the CDP's representation at 2 seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Shooters Party won the remaining seat, on 2.8% of the vote, thereby increasing their representation to 2 seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The losers from the 2007 election were the Australian Democrats, Unity Party, Outdoor Recreation Party (ORP), Human Rights Party (HRP) (formerly Reform the Legal System Party) and One Nation.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] These five parties lost their single remaining parliamentary seat, which they had won in 1999.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Australian Democrats and Unity Party polled less than 2%, ORP and HRP polled well below 1%, whilst neither One Nation, nor their former representative-turned-Independent, David Oldfield, contested the 2007 election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Members whose names are in italics retired at the election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Pittwater was won by an Independent in a 2005 by-election and the shown swing is based on it.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] At the 2003 election it was won by the Liberals.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] In 2003, Hawkesbury was won by Steve Pringle, representing the Liberals on a 14.6% margin against Labor.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] In 2006, he defected from the Liberals to become an Independent.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] In 2006, Gaudry was disendorsed by the Labor Party State executive and in January 2007, Gaudry resigned as a member of Labor and ran as an Independent.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Balmain, in Sydney's inner-western suburbs, was with Marrickville one of two seats considered potentially winnable for the Greens.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor incumbent Verity Firth suffered a 2.9% primary and 3.2% two-candidate preferred swing against the Greens, to finish on 39.2% and 53.8% respectively.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberals held on to Hawkesbury despite an independent challenge from Steven Pringle, the disendorsed Liberal incumbent.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Pringle won 28.0% of the primary vote, at the expense of Labor and other independent candidates.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Liberal candidate Ray Williams saw his primary vote dip by just 1.0%.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] In Macquarie Fields, high-profile Liberal candidate Nola Fraser achieved a 12% swing in two-party-preferred terms compared to the 2003 poll.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The incumbent, Labor's Steven Chaytor, had bowed out of the contest after being convicted for assaulting his girlfriend.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Local issues such as hospital scandals and the 2005 Macquarie Fields riots may have also contributed to the high Liberal vote.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor candidate Andrew McDonald won Macquarie Fields comfortably.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberals won Manly from the independents for the first time since the 1980s.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Sitting MP David Barr lost to future Premier Mike Baird, who increased the Liberals' primary vote by 4.4%.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] In the very safe Labor seat of Blacktown Liberal candidate Mark Spencer managed to gain a higher than average swing against incumbent Paul Gibson who then retired at the next election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Marrickville, in Sydney's inner west, was with Balmain the other seat considered potentially winnable for the Greens.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor's Carmel Tebbutt suffered a 1.1% primary and 2.6% two-candidate preferred swing against the Greens, to finish on 46.6% and 57.5% respectively.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Tebbutt won the seat in a 2005 by-election after quitting the Legislative Council, and is a senior member of the party's left wing and has a strong personal following in the area.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberals lost Pittwater to independent Alex McTaggart at a by-election called after the resignation of John Brogden.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberals' Rob Stokes won the seat back on primaries, taking 50.5% of the vote.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Independent Dubbo MP Dawn Fardell fought off a challenge from the Nationals to retain her seat.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Nationals lost ground slightly, but the seat remains one of the state's most marginal.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Star Liberal candidate Pru Goward beat off a tough fight in Goulburn with independent candidate Paul Stephenson capturing a quarter of the vote.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Goward was helped by the Nationals' decision not to run in the seat but both Labor and the Coalition lost ground.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Allegations surfaced during the campaign that Labor was assisting Stephenson's campaign.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Independent Greg Piper won the safe seat of Lake Macquarie from Labor's Jeff Hunter.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor and the Liberals lost 10.4% and 15.7% of their primary vote respectively.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Sitting Labor MP Bryce Gaudry chose to stand as an independent after being disendorsed by his party in the seat of Newcastle.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Gaudry and another independent, John Tate, both outpolled the Greens and the Liberals.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor's Jodi McKay suffered a 17.1% swing against her but won the seat on preferences.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Port Stephens Incumbent Labor MP John Bartlett retired at this election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberals' Craig Baumann added 8.7% to his party's primary vote in the seat to outpoll Labor, and narrowly defeat ALP candidate Jim Arneman.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Labor member for Swansea, Milton Orkopoulos, resigned from parliament after being charged with a number of child-sex and drug offenses.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] An expected backlash against the ALP materialised in the form of an 11.3% swing, with independent candidate Laurie Coghlan the main beneficiary.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Nonetheless, Labor candidate Robert Coombs was able to hold the seat with a comfortable majority.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Tweed, Labor's most marginal seat, fell to the Nationals' Geoff Provest.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor incumbent Neville Newell had previously served two terms (six years) in the federal seat of Richmond before his two terms (eight years) in the State Parliament.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] A swing of 7.8% meant that the seat changed from being a marginal seat for Labor to a National Party marginal.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberals lost primary votes in the seat of Wyong, bucking the statewide swing to the party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberals had disendorsed candidate Brenton Pavier after details emerged of a sex joke he had sent to friends via SMS.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberals' new candidate, Ben Morton, managed a 5.4% swing in two-party-preferred terms, not enough to take victory from Labor candidate David Harris.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Incumbent Labor MP Paul Crittenden retired at the election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] A number of MPs did not seek re-election in 2007.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Liberal MPs Andrew Tink (Epping) and Peta Seaton, (Southern Highlands) retired.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Andrew Humpherson (Davidson) lost preselection and did not contest his seat.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Nationals MP Ian Slack-Smith (Barwon) also retired.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] The Labor MPs retiring at the 2007 election were John Bartlett (Port Stephens), Paul Crittenden (Wyong), John Mills (Wallsend), Sandra Nori (Port Jackson), John Price (Maitland) and Kim Yeadon (Granville).
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Steven Chaytor (Macquarie Fields) and Milton Orkopoulos (Swansea), each arrested for violent crimes in late 2006, pulled out of the election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Carl Scully (Smithfield), dumped from the ministry for misleading parliament, chose not to recontest his seat.
[src:animal-justice-party/2007-new-south-wales-state-election] Attorney-General Bob Debus (Blue Mountains) did not seek re-election, in anticipation of a move to federal politics.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The **2011 New South Wales state election** held on Saturday, 26 March 2011.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The 16-year-incumbent Labor Party government led by Premier Kristina Keneally was defeated in a landslide by the Liberal–National Coalition opposition led by Barry O'Farrell.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor suffered a two-party swing of 16.4 points, the largest against a sitting government at any level in Australia since World War II.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] From 50 seats at dissolution, Labor was knocked down to 20 seats—the worst defeat of a sitting government in New South Wales history, and one of the worst of a state government in Australia since federation.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The Coalition picked up a 32-seat swing to win a strong majority, with 69 seats–the largest majority government, in terms of percentage of seats controlled, in NSW history.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] It is only the third time since 1941 that a NSW Labor government has been defeated.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] It was also notable in that many of Labor's safest seats, such as Newcastle and Parramatta, were won by the Liberal Party on large swings.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] This election also saw the previous record for largest percentage of seats controlled by the Coalition, which won 74.2 percent of seats (69 out of 93 seats).
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The previous record for percentage of the legislature controlled was set by Neville Wran's Labor Party in the 1981 election, in which Labor won 69 out of 99 seats (69.7 percent).
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] New South Wales has compulsory voting, with an optional preferential ballot in single-member seats for the lower house and single transferable vote with optional preferential above-the-line voting in the proportionally represented upper house.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The election was conducted by the New South Wales Electoral Commission (NSWEC).
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Future premier Dominic Perrottet and future opposition leader Mark Speakman entered parliament at this election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The centre-left Labor Party, led by Premier Kristina Keneally, and the centre-right Liberal Party, led by Leader of the Opposition Barry O'Farrell, were the two main parties in New South Wales.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] In the 2007 state election, of 93 seats total, Labor won 52 seats, the Liberals won 22 seats and the Nationals, led by Andrew Stoner, who are in coalition with the Liberals, won 13 seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Six seats were retained by independents.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Smaller parties which hold no seats in the lower house but achieved significant votes in 2007 include The Greens and the Christian Democratic Party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] On 18 October 2008, four state electorates (Lakemba, Ryde, Cabramatta, Port Macquarie) went to by-elections as a result of the resignation of the Premier, two of his ministers, and an independent who left after winning a federal by-election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The results in Ryde, Cabramatta, and Lakemba showed the largest by-election swing against Labor in its history.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Ryde, once a safe Labor seat, with a swing of 23.1 points delivered former deputy premier John Watkins' seat to Victor Dominello.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Peter Besseling, the independent candidate, won Port Macquarie, left vacant after the resignation of Nationals-turned-independent member Rob Oakeshott, over the Nationals by a two-party margin of 54.5–45.5%, despite a swing of 23.7 points to the Nationals.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The Labor Party launched their campaign on 5 February 2011 in Liverpool within the electoral district of Macquarie Fields.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Premier Keneally launched the Labor Party's campaign slogan "Protecting jobs – Supporting families".
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] In attendance for the launch were former Prime Minister Bob Hawke and former Premiers Wran and Carr.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberal and Nationals Coalition launched their campaign on 20 February 2011 at the Joan Sutherland Performing Arts Centre in Penrith within the electoral district of Penrith with the slogan: "Real Change for NSW".
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] In attendance for the launch were both Liberal and Nationals Leaders O'Farrell and Stoner as well as federal Liberal Party leader Tony Abbott, former Liberal Premiers and Leaders Greiner, Fahey, and Chikarovski.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The Coalition had been leading in opinion polling for almost three years, and were unbackable favourites throughout the campaign to win the election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The final Newspoll had support for Labor at an all-time low with 23 percent of the primary vote and 35.9 percent of the two-party vote.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Bookmakers were paying $1.01 for a Coalition win with Labor getting as much as $36 and one agency even paid out the winnings and declared the winner a week earlier.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] At one point, Labor was widely predicted to win as few as 13 seats, seven less than the actual result.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] According to several pollsters, Labor was in danger of losing several seats where it had not been seriously threatened in decades, as well as several that it had held for a century or more.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Indeed, there were concerns that Labor would not win enough seats to form a credible shadow cabinet.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberal/National Coalition won the largest proportional number of seats in NSW state history with 69 of 93 seats in the lower house (74.2 percent of the chamber)—in contrast, Labor won 69 of 99 seats (69.7 percent of the chamber) at Neville Wran's second "Wranslide" in 1981 election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor won 20 seats, the party's smallest presence in Parliament in over a century, and the worst defeat that a sitting government in NSW has ever suffered.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Many prominent Labor MPs and ministers lost their seats including Verity Firth, David Borger, Matt Brown, Jodi McKay, Virginia Judge, Phil Costa and Kevin Greene.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] In the process, the Coalition took dozens of seats in areas considered Labor heartland, such as western Sydney and the Upper Hunter—some on swings of well over 10 per cent.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberals actually won 51 seats, enough for a majority in their own right—the first time the main non-Labor party in the state had achieved this since adopting the Liberal banner in 1945.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Although O'Farrell thus had no need for the support of the Nationals, he opted to retain the Coalition.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] In the upper house however, where half of the chamber was up for election, the landslide was not enough to deliver a Coalition majority.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Three additional votes outside of the Liberal/National Coalition were required to pass legislation.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The balance of power shifted from the Greens to the Shooters and Fishers Party and Christian Democratic Party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] With two seats each held by the latter two parties, both needed to give legislative support if Labor and the Greens opposed legislation.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Where a Member of the Legislative Assembly or Legislative Council did not renominate to contest the election, their term ended at the dissolution of the parliament.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Opinion polling was conducted by firms such as Newspoll, Galaxy and Nielsen via random telephone number selection in city and country areas Sampling sizes consist of around 1200–1300 electors.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The declared margin of error is ±3 percentage points.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Graphical summary of primary voting opinion polls for the 2011 New South Wales state election (legislative assembly).
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Graphical summary of two-party-preferred opinion polling for the 2011 New South Wales state election (legislative assembly).
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Every seat in New South Wales swung to the Coalition on a two-party-preferred basis.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The Coalition won the largest government in New South Wales history in a huge landslide, while Labor suffered the largest swing against a sitting government anywhere in Australia (and on any level) since World War II, as well as one of the worst defeats of a state government since Federation.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] This led to 12 consecutive years of Coalition government in New South Wales (the longest Coalition government and the third-longest state government overall in New South Wales history), until the Coalition was narrowly defeated in 2023.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberals alone won more first preference votes than Labor (usually it takes both Coalition parties, the Liberals and the Nationals, to have a higher first preference vote than Labor).
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor only had two safe seats after the defeat, both of which were in Western Sydney.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The seats were Bankstown (on a 10.3% margin) and Liverpool (on a 14.7% margin).
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor only held five seats outside of Sydney (Cessnock, Keira, Shellharbour, Wallsend and Wollongong).
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The Nationals gained three seats from independents (Dubbo, Port Macquarie and Tamworth), which were Nationals seats held by personally popular independents.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Oakeshott and Windsor were personally popular in these seats (with Oakeshott even being an ex-National), but on traditional two-party-preferred contests, the Nationals were well ahead of Labor.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The member for Port Macquarie, Peter Besseling, was friends with Oakeshott and previously worked as his advisor, thus angering Port Macquarie locals.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] Independents held just three seats after the election: Lake Macquarie, Northern Tablelands and Sydney.
[src:animal-justice-party/2011-new-south-wales-state-election] The Greens won their first ever seat in New South Wales, the formerly-safe Labor seat of Balmain in inner-city Sydney, despite the Liberals winning the first preference vote.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The **2014 Victorian state election**, held on Saturday, 29 November 2014, was for the 58th Parliament of Victoria.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] All 88 seats in the Victorian Legislative Assembly and 40 seats in the Victorian Legislative Council were up for election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The incumbent centre-right Coalition minority government, led by Liberal Party leader and Premier Denis Napthine and National Party leader and Deputy Premier Peter Ryan, was defeated by the centre-left Labor Party opposition, led by Daniel Andrews.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The Greens won two lower house seats, their first Legislative Assembly seats in a Victorian state election, whilst increasing their share of upper house seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The new Andrews Ministry was sworn in on 4 December 2014.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Elections for the Legislative Assembly use instant-runoff voting (called preferential voting in Australia) in single-member electorates (called districts).
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Elections for the Legislative Council use partial proportional representation, using single transferable vote (also called preferential voting) in multi-member electorates (called regions).
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Members of the Legislative Council are elected from eight electoral regions each returning five members, making the quota for election in each region 16.67%.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The election was conducted by the Victorian Electoral Commission (VEC).
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The election marked the first time since 1955 that a Victorian state government had been defeated after only one parliamentary term.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Furthermore, the Nationals were reduced to a total of ten seats in the Legislative Assembly and Legislative Council, one short of official status in the legislature.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Following the election, both Napthine and Ryan resigned as leaders of the Liberal and National parties, respectively.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Terms are fixed at four years unless dissolved earlier by the Governor.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The election occurred in line with the fixed-term provisions laid out in the *Electoral Act 2002*.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The Coalition won the 2010 Victorian state election, winning 45 seats in the 88-member lower house, a swing of 12 seats, defeating the 11-year Labor government which won 43 seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Labor suffered a swing of 5.96 percent, a larger swing than the 1992 landslide that brought the Jeff Kennett-led Coalition to power.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] This led Paul Austin of the *Sydney Morning Herald* to speculate that Labor was headed for a long period in the political wilderness.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] However, by 2012, Labor had gradually whittled away a large Coalition advantage in opinion polling.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] By the time the writs were dropped, Labor had been leading most opinion polls for almost two years, though Andrews consistently trailed as preferred premier.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] With a Coalition MP as Speaker, the government operated with a one-seat margin of 44 seats, until the resignation of Geoff Shaw, the member for Frankston, from the Liberal Party on 6 March 2013.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] This meant the government had only 43 votes on the floor of the parliament, equal to Labor's total.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Partly due to Shaw's defection, Premier Ted Baillieu resigned later on 6 March and was succeeded as Liberal leader and Premier by Ports Minister Denis Napthine.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] If this had happened, his actions could have precipitated an early state election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The government operated with a two-seat margin in the 40-member upper house where all members are up for re-election every term, with 21 Coalition, 16 Labor and 3 Greens members.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Labor retained seats at the Broadmeadows, Niddrie, Melbourne and Lyndhurst by-elections.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Their seats were filled by Cesar Melhem, Marg Lewis, Amanda Millar, and Andrew Ronalds respectively, each being appointed by a joint sitting of Parliament.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Additionally, two other parties applied for registration prior to the election, but failed to achieve registration by the deadline: No East West Link and Save the Planet.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] A redistribution of Victoria's state electoral boundaries took place from 2012 to 2013.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The final boundaries were gazetted on 17 October 2013 and were used for the 2014 state election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Five electorates changed parties notionally with the new boundaries, including Wendouree, a notional Liberal seat created from the Labor seat of Ballarat West.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] According to ABC psephologist Antony Green, the Labor-held seats of Bellarine, Monbulk, Ripon and Yan Yean became notionally Liberal.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] This meant that Labor needed a notional five-seat swing to win government.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Much of the Labor campaign was focused on the Napthine Government's A$18 billion East West Link toll road project, which Labor opposed, and said it would halt if it won power.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] In early November Prime Minister Tony Abbott, in one of his few Victorian appearances for the Liberals during the campaign, described the election as "a referendum on the East West Link".
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Public transport also featured strongly during the campaign, with the parties presenting rival inner-city rail tunnel projects and competing plans to remove railway level crossings to ease road congestion.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] With unemployment at its highest level since 2001, jobs and the economy became a key issue and both sides promised major job creation schemes: the Coalition said it would create 200,000 jobs over five years and Labor said it would create 100,000 jobs within two years.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Other major issues raised during the election were the long-running Ambulance Victoria industrial dispute and slow ambulance response times, urban planning laws, education and law and order.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Both major parties promised to build new and bigger hospitals.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Labor election advertising aimed to capitalise on the unpopularity of Australia's Liberal Prime Minister and unpopular federal Liberal policies, while much of the Coalition advertising depicted Andrews as a leader with close ties to the Construction, Forestry, Mining and Energy Union.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] On environmental issues neither the Coalition nor Labor presented comprehensive policies, although Labor promised to repeal some of the Coalition's legislation, such as on cattle grazing in the Alpine National Park and leases in national parks.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] A key topic was the proposal for a new Great Forest National Park, that was opposed by the Coalition and was not supported by Labor.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The Greens supported the new park, as well as stronger action on climate change and phase-out of coal fired power stations.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] As the close of nominations on 14 November 2014, there were a total of 896 candidates in the election (a 26 per cent increase to the 711 candidates in the 2010 election).
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] There were 545 candidates contesting the 88 seats of the Victorian Legislative Assembly (up from 501, an 8.6 per cent increase); and 351 candidates contesting the 40 seats in the Legislative Council (up from 206, a 68 per cent increase).
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Labor and the Greens contested every electorate.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] There were 92 candidates from the Liberal–National Coalition for the lower house, with four "three-cornered contests" where both Liberal and National candidates contested the same seat (Buninyong, Eildon, Euroa and Ripon).
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Polling that is conducted by Newspoll and published in *The Australian* is conducted via random telephone number selection in city and country areas.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Sampling sizes usually consist of around 1100–1200 electors.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Following the election, the seats of Frankston and Prahran were initially too close to call, with around a hundred votes separating candidates.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Prahran was a three-way contest between Labor, Liberal, and the Greens, and this seat proved to be the tightest contest among all the lower house seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The VEC declared Prahran had been won by the Greens on 9 December, whereby the Greens overtook the ALP from third place, to defeat the Liberal incumbent in the final distribution of preferences.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The Greens' win was confirmed in the recount held the following day.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] to take account of the 2013 redistribution.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] As such, it may vary from 2010 election results.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] The seats of Bellarine, Monbulk, Ripon, and Yan Yean were won by Labor at the 2010 election, but redistributions in 2013 made them notionally Liberal seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Similarly, the redistribution largely replaced Ballarat West with Wendouree; Ballarat West was also won by Labor at the 2010 election, but notionally Liberal post-redistribution.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] , which was largely replaced with Wendouree by the redistribution.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] In January 2015, unsuccessful Palmer United Party candidate Maria Rigoni petitioned the Supreme Court of Victoria to declare the 2014 election invalid, alleging that the Victorian Electoral Commission had breached the Electoral Act whilst conducting the election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Rigoni argued that the unprecedented high level of early voting demonstrated that the VEC had not applied or enforced the rule requiring applicants for an early or postal votes to declare a valid reason to an electoral officer that they were unable to vote on polling day.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] Lawyers acting for the VEC asked the court to dismiss the case as an abuse of process, however Justice Jack Forrest disagreed, and set the case to proceed to trial on 25 February 2015.
[src:animal-justice-party/2014-victorian-state-election] On 24 March, Justice Gregory Garde of the Supreme Court of Victoria dismissed Rigoni's case, ruling that there was no evidence presented to the court that the VEC's early voting procedures had any effect on the result.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The **2015 New South Wales state election** was held on Saturday 28 March 2015.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Members were elected to all 93 seats in the Legislative Assembly using optional preferential voting.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Members were also elected to 21 of the 42 seats in the Legislative Council using optional preferential proportional representation voting.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The election was conducted by the New South Wales Electoral Commission.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The one-term incumbent Liberal/National Coalition Government led by Premier Mike Baird and Deputy Premier Troy Grant was re-elected to a second four-year term with a reduced majority in the Legislative Assembly.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The main Opposition Labor Party under Luke Foley won an increased share of the vote in most districts, though the party lost ground in some key races, including Foley's seat of Auburn.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] It managed to take 11 seats off the Coalition and Coalition-turned independents, mostly in areas of Labor "heartland" lost to the Liberals during the landslide in 2011, but nevertheless the Liberals still won a second consecutive landslide with a 15-seat majority.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Most notably, Labor regained seats in west Sydney, the Central Coast and the lower Hunter.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Baird had campaigned on a controversial plan to lease 49 per cent of the state-owned electricity distribution network (known as the "poles and wires") to deliver an ambitious transport and social infrastructure program.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor, supported by the state's union movement, ran on an anti-privatisation platform, while also promising a moratorium on coal-seam gas (CSG) extraction, and encouraging voters to register a protest vote against the Liberal-led Coalition federal government.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Although the poles-and-wires proposal was poorly received in opinion polls, Baird himself was widely liked by the electorate.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Candidate nominations closed on 12 March and early voting began on 16 March.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Eleven seats won by the Liberals and Nationals in 2011 went to other parties in 2015.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Incumbent Liberal MPs were defeated by Labor challengers in Blue Mountains, Campbelltown, Granville, Rockdale and Strathfield.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Incumbents Don Page (a National) and Robyn Parker (a Liberal) retired, with the Greens taking Page's seat of Ballina and Labor taking Parker's seat of Maitland.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Londonderry, Port Stephens and Wyong, whose Liberal incumbents had been sitting as independents since 2013 and retired in 2015, returned to Labor.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Former Liberal Edwards, in Swansea, re-contested the seat as an independent but lost to Labor challenger Yasmin Catley.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Miranda Labor MP Collier had retired at the 2011 election, with the Liberals' Annesley picking up the seat on a swing of nearly 22 points.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] When Annesley quit politics in 2013, Collier returned to contest the by-election, securing a 27-point swing – the largest-ever at a NSW by-election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Collier decided not to re-contest the seat in 2015, and the Liberals' Eleni Petinos took it with 63 per cent of the two-party-preferred vote.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Northern Tablelands, won by an independent in 2011 and lost to the Nationals in 2013, was retained by the Nationals.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Charlestown and Newcastle, won by the Liberals in 2011 and lost to Labor at by-elections in 2014, were retained by Labor.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Following the 2013 redistribution (see below) the ABC recalculated the 2011 election results based on the new boundaries.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] These calculations deemed Macquarie Fields, a Labor marginal, notionally Liberal.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The new seat of Prospect, which replaced Liberal-held Smithfield, was also considered notionally Liberal, albeit by a reduced margin.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In Macquarie Fields, incumbent Labor MP Andrew McDonald did not re-contest and Labor candidate Anoulack Chanthivong defeated Liberal Pat Farmer.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In Prospect, the sitting Smithfield MP, Andrew Rohan, was defeated by Labor candidate Hugh McDermott.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Holsworthy replaced the abolished seat of Menai which was held by sitting member Melanie Gibbons, who retained the newly created seat.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Macquarie Fields become notionally Liberal with a margin of 1.8.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The sitting member, Andrew McDonald retired at the 2015 election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The seat of Marrickville held by former deputy premier Carmel Tebbutt, who retired at the 2015 election, was abolished and divided into Newtown and Summer Hill.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] which was held by former premier Nathan Rees, who retired at the 2015 election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The seat became notionally Liberal in the redistribution.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Prospect replaced Smithfield and became notionally weaker for the Liberal Party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor governed NSW from 1995 until 2011.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Over the course of its last two terms, a succession of leadership changes, criminal convictions, corruption scandals and cancelled infrastructure projects began to eat away at Labor's support base.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In a harbinger of things to come, the previously safe Labor seats of Ryde and Penrith were both resoundingly lost to the Liberals, in both cases turning into safe Liberal seats in one stroke.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In March 2011, the Liberals and Nationals, led by the Liberals' Barry O'Farrell, won one of the most comprehensive state-level victories since Federation, taking 69 seats in the Legislative Assembly.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In 2013, the Nationals won a by-election in Northern Tablelands after independent MP Richard Torbay resigned over corruption allegations.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The win in Northern Tablelands represented the high point for the Government party room.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] At the next by-election, caused when Sports Minister and member for Miranda Graham Annesley resigned to take a job in Queensland, the Liberals suffered the largest two-party-preferred swing in state history—26 points—and former MP Barry Collier reclaimed the seat for Labor.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Things got worse for the Government when news broke of Operation Spicer, an Independent Commission Against Corruption investigation into allegedly illegal campaign donations to a number of Liberal MPs from the Hunter and Central Coast.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Bart Bassett, MP for the Western Sydney seat of Londonderry, was also implicated and quit the parliamentary party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Cornwell and Owen later resigned from parliament following damning evidence presented at the Spicer public hearing, triggering by-elections in Charlestown and Newcastle.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In what the Liberals described as an "act of atonement" for Owen and Cornwell's actions, the party did not contest either by-election, and Labor easily reclaimed both seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] All but Edwards indicated their intention not to stand for re-election in 2015 (Gallacher's Legislative Council term does not expire until 2019); Edwards would be heavily defeated by Labor's Catley.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] However, Spicer's biggest scalp was that of Premier O'Farrell, who found he'd inadvertently misled the Commission over a bottle of wine he'd received as a gift from lobbyist Nick Di Girolamo.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] O'Farrell called a press conference and announced his resignation on 17 April 2014.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The frontrunners to replace him were Treasurer Mike Baird and Transport Minister Gladys Berejiklian, though in the event Baird stood unopposed, with Berejiklian elected unopposed as his deputy.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] A Cabinet reshuffle followed, with ministers Robyn Parker, Don Page, Greg Smith and George Souris dumped to make way for Troy Grant, Jai Rowell, Rob Stokes and Paul Toole.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The Nationals followed suit six months later, with leader and Deputy Premier Andrew Stoner stepping down due to undisclosed family issues on 15 October.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Stoner was quickly removed from Cabinet, replaced by John Barilaro; Grant succeeded him as Nationals leader and Deputy Premier.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Soon after taking office, Baird and Grant put a massive infrastructure program, funded by partial privatisation of the state's electricity networks, at the heart of the Government's re-election campaign.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor soon faced leadership problems of its own.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In the aftermath of a hostage drama at a café in central Sydney, it emerged that Opposition Leader John Robertson had, in his capacity as member for Blacktown, made a representation on behalf of the gunman, Man Haron Monis, three years earlier.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Facing threats of being voted out, Robertson stepped down on 23 December.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Though frontbenchers Michael Daley and Steve Whan considered running, both men withdrew in favour of the party's Planning spokesman and leader in the Legislative Council, Luke Foley.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Working in the Government's favour was a highly popular leader and a fully funded plan to build additional roads and rail lines in Sydney, easing congestion.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] However, the Government now faced significant headwinds on its way to the March election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The Opposition had a new leader relatively untainted by the corruption that had marred the previous Labor government.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The federal Liberal/National government in Canberra was unpopular following a poorly received austerity budget.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Their policy platform was a form of privatisation, something with limited electoral appeal, that sparked a well-resourced union scare campaign.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Lingering anger over revelations from Operation Spicer remained in many seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In regional areas, the Nationals had long faced a scare campaign on coal-seam gas.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Earlier, first-term conservative premiers had been toppled in Victoria, then Queensland.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The 2007 and 2011 elections were conducted using boundaries set in 2004.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The state constitution requires the Electoral Commission to review electoral district boundaries after every two elections, to ensure that the number of voters in each district is within 10 per cent of the "quota" – the number of voters divided by the number of Legislative Assembly seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In 2012, the Commission began work on determining new boundaries for the 2015 election, a process commonly known as "redistribution".
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The quota was 52,770, meaning that each district needed to have between 47,000 and 58,000 enrolled electors.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The Nationals-held district of Murrumbidgee was abolished, and the Nationals-held districts of Burrinjuck and Murray-Darling renamed Cootamundra and Murray respectively.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Burrinjuck MP Katrina Hodgkinson initially announced her intention to run for Goulburn, taking on her cabinet colleague, Liberal Pru Goward, on the grounds that much of the area she now represented would be in the Goulburn district come 2015.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] O'Farrell reportedly persuaded Hodgkinson to back down, to avoid splitting the conservative vote and potentially losing Goulburn to Labor.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Hodgkinson went on to contest Cootamundra, while Murrumbidgee MP Adrian Piccoli contested Murray and Murray-Darling MP John Williams joined the party's upper house ticket.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In Sydney, replaced Liberal-held Menai was renamed Holsworthy, Liberal-held Smithfield was renamed Prospect, Labor-held Toongabbie was renamed Seven Hills, and Labor-held Marrickville was renamed Summer Hill.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] A new inner-city district, Newtown, was also created.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Based on 2011 voting patterns, the ABC calculated that Seven Hills and Macquarie Fields were notionally Liberal seats, while Newtown was notionally Greens-held.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The new boundaries were gazetted on 18 September 2013, with effect from the 2015 election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The ABC calculated that in 2011 the new boundaries would have increased Liberal representation from 51 to 53, reduced Nationals representation from 18 to 17, increased Greens representation from one to two, and reduced Labor representation from 20 to 18.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Mike Baird MP (born 1 April 1968) was the 44th Premier of New South Wales, the Minister for Infrastructure, the Minister for Western Sydney, and the Leader of the New South Wales Liberal Party from April 2014 until January 2017.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] He represented the New South Wales Legislative Assembly seat of Manly for the Liberal Party of Australia from 2007 until 2017.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Before becoming Premier, he was the Treasurer of New South Wales in the O'Farrell government between 2011 and 2014.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Baird has completed a Bachelor of Arts (Economics) at the University of Sydney and previously worked as an investment banker at Deutsche Bank, NAB and HSBC.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Baird is married to Kerryn and they have three children.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Luke Foley took over as Labor leader from Robertson following the latter's resignation in December 2014.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Foley had initially faced two challengers for the job – Michael Daley and Steve Whan – though both men ultimately withdrew from the race.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] As a member of the Legislative Council, Foley was required by convention to seek a seat in the Legislative Assembly, and so nominated for the inner western Sydney seat of Auburn.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Both the incumbent MP, Barbara Perry, and her preselection challenger, Hicham Zraika, withdrew, allowing Foley to take the nomination unopposed.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] During the campaign, Foley was unable to match his opponent's appeal, consistently recording net satisfaction ratings under 10 and "better premier" ratings around half that of Baird's (see below).
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Hailing from the party's Socialist Left faction, Foley is a former National Union of Students president, Australian Services Union state secretary, Labor assistant state secretary and parliamentary staffer.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In the Legislative Council, Foley served as both Opposition Leader in that House and the party's shadow minister for Planning.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Foley is married to Edel McKenna and they have three children.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Before the election, the governing Liberal and National parties held 42 and 19 seats, respectively.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The main opposition Labor party held 23.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The crossbench was composed of nine MPs: the Greens' Jamie Parker; independents Alex Greenwich and Greg Piper; and six MPs elected as Liberals in 2011 but who resigned from the parliamentary party following ICAC's Operation Spicer.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In 2015, the Liberals contested 74 seats and the Nationals 19.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] (The 2013 redistribution eliminated one Nationals seat in south-western NSW.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The only Labor-held seat in which the Nationals stood a candidate was Cessnock.) Labor contested all 93 seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Of the crossbenchers, only Parker, Greenwich and Piper recontested, along with former Liberal Garry Edwards.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] All six parties represented before the election in the Legislative Council nominated candidates.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] As in previous elections, the governing Liberal and National parties fielded a joint ticket.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Between them, the parties won eight Council seats in 2007, among them the seats of ministers John Ajaka and Matthew Mason-Cox.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Eleven Liberal and Nationals members of the Legislative Council (MLCs) were elected in 2011 and did not face election in 2015.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The 2015 ticket was headed by Ajaka for the Liberals and, facing his first electoral test, the former Nationals State Director Ben Franklin.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberals and Nationals directed their Legislative Council preferences, indeed "swap preferences", to the Christian Democrats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The Labor ticket was branded as "Labor / Country Labor".
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor won nine Council seats in 2007, among them the seat occupied by Foley.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] (Foley was appointed to fill the seat left vacant by the resignation in 2010 of disgraced former minister Ian Macdonald.) Five Labor MLCs were elected in 2011 and did not face election in 2015.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The 2015 Labor ticket was headed by former union official Sophie Cotsis.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor directed its Legislative Council preferences to the Greens.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The Greens won two seats in 2007 – by Lee Rhiannon (now a federal NSW senator) and John Kaye.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Rhiannon was later replaced by Cate Faehrmann, who in turn was replaced by Mehreen Faruqi.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Three Greens MLCs were elected in 2011 and did not face election in 2015.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The Greens directed their Legislative Council preferences to what they considered as 'progressive' micro parties, followed by Labor.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The Christian Democratic Party (CDP) had two seats, of which one faced election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Party leader Fred Nile headed the 2015 ticket.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The CDP directed their Legislative Council preferences to, indeed "swap preferences with", the Liberals and Nationals.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The Shooters and Fishers Party (SFP) had two seats, of which one faced election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Incumbent Robert Borsak headed the 2015 ticket.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Two MLCs elected as Liberals, former Police Minister Mike Gallacher and former Hurstville mayor Marie Ficarra, had sat as independents following Operation Spicer.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Ficarra, whose term expired in 2015, did not recontest.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Gallacher, who was re-elected in 2011, remained an MLC.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Eight groups nominated without a registered party name.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Seventeen candidates nominated without groups.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Former Premier O'Farrell (Liberal, Ku-ring-gai) did not re-contest his seat, along with dumped former ministers Greg Smith (Liberal, Epping), Don Page (Nationals, Ballina), Robyn Parker (Liberal, Maitland), George Souris (Nationals, Upper Hunter) and Andrew Stoner (Nationals, Oxley).
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Long-serving MLCs Charlie Lynn (Liberal) and Jenny Gardiner (Nationals) also announced they would not be running again.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Lynn, then aged 70, planned to run for the state presidency of the Returned and Services League.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] All but two of the former Liberal MPs implicated by Operation Spicer announced they would not re-contest: Bassett (Londonderry), Baumann (Port Stephens), Hartcher (Terrigal), Spence (The Entrance), Webber (Wyong) and Ficarra (Legislative Council).
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] On the Labor side, Barbara Perry, who had been facing a preselection challenge for her seat of Auburn, withdrew to allow Foley to win Labor's nomination unopposed.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberal campaign slogans were "Back Baird" and "Keep NSW Working".
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In January 2015, Labor leader Luke Foley announced a policy to create a Great Koala National Park and hold a koala summit.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Baird sought a mandate to lease 49% of the government's electricity distributors, known locally as the "poles and wires", for 99 years and invest the proceeds in new road, public transport, water, health and education infrastructure.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] With opposition to the lease forming the centrepiece of Labor's campaign, the election was widely viewed as a referendum on the proposal.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The government's plan involved the lease of 100% of high-voltage distributor TransGrid and majority stakes in Ausgrid and Endeavour Energy, which together cover local distribution in metropolitan NSW.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Country-based Essential Energy was not part of the proposal.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The proceeds, estimated at $20 billion, were to be spent on major projects including an extension of the under-construction North West Rail Link to the city centre and on to Bankstown.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The plan enjoyed support, from business groups, such as the Energy Users' Association, the Business Council and the Australian Industry Group; and by transport lobby groups Infrastructure Partnerships Australia and the Tourism and Transport Forum.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In addition, a number of senior Labor figures came out in support, including former Prime Minister Paul Keating, former NSW Treasurer Michael Costa, and former federal Resources Minister Martin Ferguson.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Following the election, former Labor Premiers Bob Carr and Morris Iemma and former Labor Treasurer Michael Egan added their voices in support.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Full privatisation of poles and wires also had the support of Australia's Productivity Commission.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The plan was opposed by Labor, the Greens, the Shooters & Fishers and a number of unions.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The plan also polled poorly and attracted little support on the ABC's *Vote Compass* site.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The party's claims on price increases were debunked by separate reports from Australian Broadcasting Corporation, Deloitte Access Economics and the Grattan Institute.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Dr Tom Parry, formerly the head of NSW's Independent Pricing and Regulatory Tribunal, told *The Australian* "all the evidence" was that privatised networks "have much better cost controls ...
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Some of the most savage criticism came from within the Labor party itself.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Keating dismissed the campaign as the work of "some obscurantists".
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Foley's suggestion that Chinese investment represented a national security risk was dismissed as racist "dog-whistle politics" by treasurer Andrew Constance and Egan.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Federal Race Discrimination Commissioner Tim Soutphommasane, himself a former Labor staffer, implored Labor and the unions on Twitter not to "licence xenophobia".
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Coal-seam gas (CSG) extraction became a major issue, particularly on the fringes of the metropolitan area and in the Northern Rivers region.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] When it left office, Labor had awarded CSG licences covering about 60 per cent of the state's land area.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberals and Nationals also supported CSG as a means to create regional jobs and prevent an expected increase in domestic natural gas prices.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Responding to what was described as "a climate of community unease" about land access and the possibility of environmental damage, the Government asked the state's independent Chief Scientist, Professor Mary O'Kane, to review the CSG industry in NSW.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] O'Kane concluded that "the technical challenges and risks posed by the CSG industry can in general be managed", allowing extraction to continue.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Nonetheless, the Government had gas firms hand back many of the most contentious outstanding undeveloped licences in Sydney, the Central Coast and the Northern Rivers.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor promised to go further, simply banning CSG extraction statewide, an approach which would have led to higher natural gas prices, triggered compensation payments to gas investors and, according to the industry, revealed "a stubborn refusal to face the facts" in the light of the O'Kane report.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The Greens, who had always opposed CSG, went on to beat Labor into second place on primary votes in two Nationals-held Northern Rivers seats, Ballina and Lismore.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In December 2013, the government had suspended services on the surface-level train line that separates the Newcastle city centre from the Hunter River waterfront.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The line had long been considered an impediment to the city's development, and the government's plan was to close the line and build a light rail system in its place.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor, which had advocated for such a plan in government, now led opposition to it.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor criticised alleged cuts to health and education.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor attacked Baird for his former career in banking and his friendship with prime minister Tony Abbott, whose electorate of Warringah overlaps Baird's seat of Manly.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] At the time of the election, Abbott was polling poorly.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In an echo of the Liberals' successful 2004 campaign against then Opposition Leader Mark Latham, the Government branded Foley an 'L-plate' leader on the basis of his lack of ministerial and leadership experience.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Baird's campaign bus was attacked by graffiti vandals during an overnight stop in Katoomba.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Foley later joked on radio: “Fancy leaving your bus out overnight in Katoomba, unguarded.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] I’m surprised there are still wheels." Foley's comments drew criticism from both Blue Mountains MP Roza Sage and the local Chamber of Commerce.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] An error on the Electoral Commission's "iVote" electronic pre-poll voting system reportedly omitted the Animal Justice Party from the "above the line" section of the Legislative Council ballot for 36 hours, during which time 19,000 votes were cast.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Animal Justice, a micro-party that received less than two per cent of the vote, is nonetheless considered a contender for the 21st and final Council seat, thanks to a preference deal with the Greens.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The party's lead candidate, Mark Pearson, said he was considering legal action if he did not gain a seat.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] On 26 March, a 20-year-old Liberal campaign volunteer in Cabramatta was allegedly struck by a Labor volunteer during an altercation outside a pre-poll centre.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] A video of the incident was captured by the alleged victim on her mobile phone.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Police were reportedly investigating the incident.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] East Hills Labor candidate Cameron Murphy alleged he had been the victim of a dirty tricks campaign, involving leaflets and stickers branding the civil libertarian as a "paedophile lover" because of his work as president of the NSW Council for Civil Liberties.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] East Hills, held by Labor continuously from 1953 to 2011, was won in 2011 by Liberal Glenn Brookes with a margin of 0.2 points (adjusting for boundary changes in 2013).
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Murphy told the press he had lodged a complaint with the Electoral Commission and was seeking legal advice.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] The newly registered No Land Tax Party fielded candidates in all 93 electoral districts, thus maximising their chances of receiving public funding.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Party leader Peter Jones conceded he had not met half of the candidates, many of whom did not live in the districts they hoped to represent.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In Bega, held by Treasurer Andrew Constance for the Liberals, reports surfaced during the campaign that No Land Tax candidate Clyde Archard had in fact died in Borneo as a prisoner of war in 1945.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] He nonetheless received 2.3 per cent of the vote.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] In the final week of the campaign, the Liberals and Nationals received the endorsement of the main daily and Sunday newspapers in the state: *The Australian*, *The Australian Financial Review*, *The Daily Telegraph*, *The Sunday Telegraph*, *The Sun-Herald* and *The Sydney Morning Herald*.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Election night coverage was provided by the ABC, Seven, Nine and Sky News Australia.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Collectively, the three free-to-air programs had 371,000 viewers in the Sydney market.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor supporters gathered at Dooley's Catholic Club in Lidcombe.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Foley conceded defeat at 9.20 pm, saying "a majority of voters have decided that now is too soon for Labor to return to government." Liberal supporters gathered at Sydney's Sofitel Sydney Wentworth, where Baird claimed victory at 9.45 pm.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] On 1 April Baird announced a reshuffle of the ministry.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] His deputy, Berejiklian, was promoted to Treasurer, while Constance moved to Transport.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Nationals leader Grant took on Justice and Police.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Rob Stokes was promoted from Environment to Planning; Gabrielle Upton from Community Services to Attorney-General.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Goward was demoted from Planning to Mental Health.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Ministers Hodgkinson and Mason-Cox, along with Liberal Jai Rowell and National Kevin Humphries were dropped from the ministry in favour of Liberals David Elliott and Mark Speakman and Nationals Niall Blair and Leslie Williams.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] On election night Foley told supporters he intended to stay on as party leader.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Daley, his former leadership rival, ruled out a challenge, saying the party was in a "rebuilding phase".
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] A number of campaign workers for the No Land Tax Party came forward after the election claiming they had not been paid as promised by party leader Peter Jones.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Others claimed they had signed up thinking they would be working for the Electoral Commission.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Several research, media and polling firms conduct opinion polls during the parliamentary term and prior to the state election in relation to voting.
[src:animal-justice-party/2015-new-south-wales-state-election] Most firms use the flow of preferences at the previous election to determine the two-party-preferred vote; others ask respondents to nominate preferences.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-lord-mayor-of-melbourne-by-election] The **2018 Melbourne lord mayoral by-election** was held from 23 April until 11 May 2018 to elect the Lord Mayor of Melbourne, following the resignation of Robert Doyle.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-lord-mayor-of-melbourne-by-election] The election used a preferential voting system and was held by postal ballot.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-lord-mayor-of-melbourne-by-election] The City of Melbourne is a local government municipality consisting of nine councillors, a lord mayor and a deputy lord mayor, who are elected for a four-year term.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-lord-mayor-of-melbourne-by-election] The incumbent lord mayor, Robert Doyle, was first elected in the 2008 City of Melbourne election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-lord-mayor-of-melbourne-by-election] On 15 December 2017, Cr Tessa Sullivan resigned from the council.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-lord-mayor-of-melbourne-by-election] Sullivan, who had been elected on the Team Doyle ticket alongside Doyle, lodged a complaint with the City of Melbourne chief executive Ben Rimmer.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-lord-mayor-of-melbourne-by-election] In her complaint, Sullivan alleged that Doyle had sexually harassed and indecently assaulted her.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-lord-mayor-of-melbourne-by-election] On 17 December, Doyle released a statement on Twitter, which said he had not been informed of the details of the allegations.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-lord-mayor-of-melbourne-by-election] He announced he would take a month's leave while an investigation was carried out, stressing that his standing aside "must not be interpreted as any concession or admission".
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-lord-mayor-of-melbourne-by-election] Further allegations were made against Doyle in January 2018.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-lord-mayor-of-melbourne-by-election] On 4 February 2018, Doyle resigned as Lord Mayor of Melbourne.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The **2018 Victorian state election** was held on Saturday, 24 November 2018 to elect the 59th Parliament of Victoria.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] All 88 seats in the Legislative Assembly (lower house) and all 40 seats in the Legislative Council (upper house) were up for election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The first-term incumbent Labor government, led by Premier Daniel Andrews, won a second four-year term, defeating the Liberal/National Coalition opposition, led by Opposition Leader Matthew Guy in a landslide victory.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Greens, a minor party led by Samantha Ratnam also contested the election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Labor won 55 seats in the 88-seat Legislative Assembly, an increase of eight seats from the previous election in 2014, and a majority of 22 seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] This was the fifth time that a Labor government was re-elected in Victoria, and it tied Victorian Labor's second-best showing at the state level.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Coalition suffered an 11-seat swing against it, and won 27 seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Greens won three seats, a net increase of one seat since the last election though equal to the share of seats they held when the election was called.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The remaining three seats on the crossbench were won by independents.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] In the Legislative Council, Labor won 18 seats, three short of a majority.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Coalition won 11 seats, and the remaining 11 seats were won by a range of minor parties from across the political spectrum.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Several days after Labor's victory, the Second Andrews Ministry was sworn in by the Governor and was notable for featuring an equal number of men and women.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The following week the Liberal Party elected Michael O'Brien leader of the party, who became Opposition Leader in the new parliament, after Guy had announced earlier he would stand down from the position.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] For the election, Victoria had compulsory voting and used majoritarian preferential voting in single-member seats for the Legislative Assembly, and Single transferable vote (STV) in multi-member seats for the proportionally represented Legislative Council.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Legislative Council had 40 members serving four-year terms, elected from eight electoral regions each with five members.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Victorian Legislative Council uses Group Voting Tickets.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] With each region electing five members, the quota in each region for election, after distribution of preferences, was 16.7% (one-sixth) of the valid votes cast in that district.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The election was conducted by the Victorian Electoral Commission (VEC), an independent body answerable to parliament.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Pursuant to the *Electoral Act 2002*, Victoria has had fixed terms, with all elections since the 2006 election held every four years on the last Saturday of November.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The incumbent government entered into caretaker mode at 6:00 pm on Tuesday, 30 October 2018, when writs were officially issued.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Following the 2014 election, Labor formed majority government with 47 seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Coalition held 38 seats, with the Liberal Party holding 30 and the National Party holding 8.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] On the crossbench, the Greens held 2 seats and Independent Suzanna Sheed held the seat of Shepparton.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Following the 2014 election, Labor held 14 seats; the Coalition held 16 seats (14 Liberal, 2 National); the Greens held 5 seats; the Shooters, Fishers and Farmers Party held 2 seats; and the Sex Party (now the Reason Party), Democratic Labour Party, and Vote 1 Local Jobs party held 1 seat each.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Former Nationals leader Peter Ryan announced his resignation from parliament on 2 February 2015, triggering a by-election in the seat of Gippsland South for 14 March.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The election was won by Danny O'Brien of the National Party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Denis Napthine and Terry Mulder resigned from parliament on 3 September 2015.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Their seats were retained by the Liberal Party in by-elections held in South-West Coast and Polwarth on 31 October.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Minister for Women and Minister for the Prevention of Family Violence Fiona Richardson died on 23 August 2017.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] A by-election was held in the seat of Northcote on 18 November, in which the Victorian Greens won the seat from the Labor Party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Don Nardella, the former Deputy Speaker of the Assembly and member for the seat of Melton, resigned from the Labor Party on 7 March 2017 to sit as an independent.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Nardella's resignation was demanded by Premier Andrews after Nardella refused to pay back approximately $100,000 of taxpayer funded entitlements in the midst an expenses scandal.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The resignation reduced the number of Labor members in the Assembly from 47 to 46, still above the 45 seats needed for majority government to be formed.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Nardella had previously announced his intention to quit politics at the 2018 election and following his resignation from the Labor Party stated he intended to serve out his full term as the member for Melton.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Russell Northe, the member for Morwell resigned from the National Party on 28 August 2017, due to mental health and financial issues, continuing in his position as an independent.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Greg Barber resigned as Leader of the Greens and from his Northern Metropolitan Region seat on 28 September 2017, and was replaced in both by Moreland councillor Samantha Ratnam.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Colleen Hartland, a Greens member of the Western Metropolitan Region, resigned on 8 February 2018, and was replaced by Huong Truong.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The following Mackerras pendulum lists seats in the Legislative Assembly according to the percentage point margin on a two candidate preferred basis based on the 2014 election results.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Australian Electoral Commission considers a seat "safe" if it requires a swing of over 10% to change, "fairly safe" seats require a swing of between 6 and 10%, while "marginal" seats require a swing of less than 6%.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Nominations of candidates opened on 31 October 2018.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Nominations for party candidates closed on 8 November, and for independent candidates on 9 November.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] A total of 887 candidates nominated for the election, down from 896 at the 2014 election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] There were 507 candidates for the Legislative Assembly, the second-highest number on record, down from 545 in 2014.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The 380 candidates for the Legislative Council was the highest number of upper house candidates in a Victorian election, up from 351 in 2014.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] On 13 November, Neelam Rai, a Liberal candidate for Northern Metropolitan Region, withdrew her candidacy after the *Herald Sun* revealed that she was the director of an unregistered charity, No Hunger Australia.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Liberal Party also released a statement saying that Rai's nomination form for preselection had "failed to disclose a number of issues of relevance".
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] On 15 November, the Liberal Party withdrew its endorsement of Meralyn Klein, their candidate for the marginal seat of Yan Yean, after footage emerged of her speaking in an anti-Muslim video produced by the Australian Liberty Alliance.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Klein denied any association with the ALA, saying she had been interviewed about an incident where she had been assaulted several years earlier, and the footage had been provided to the ALA and edited into an anti-Muslim video.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] As ballot papers had already been printed, both Rai and Klein appeared as Liberal candidates.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Labor Party petitioned the Supreme Court to order the VEC to reprint the ballot papers with Klein's affiliation removed, but the case was dismissed.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] On 22 November, two days before Election Day, the Greens ordered a then-unnamed candidate to withdraw from the campaign after an allegation of "serious sexual misconduct" was made.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The following day the party revealed the candidate in question was Dominic Phillips, candidate for the seat of Sandringham; he was stood down by the party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] As the ballot papers had already been printed, Phillips stood as the Greens candidate and won over 8% of the vote.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Labor and the Coalition pledged $23.3 billion and $24.8 billion respectively, more than double pledged during the 2010 and 2014 elections, excluding the proposed Suburban Rail Loop and high speed rail for regional services which would require future governments to fund.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Coalition's leading message of the campaign was to "get back in control" of the state's allegedly burgeoning crime problem.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The party promised tougher bail conditions than Labor, saying that anyone who breaches bail will be jailed.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The divisions between the parties over social issues were pronounced, as the Coalition promised to axe the safe injecting room in Richmond, the Safe Schools program for LGBTI children in state secondary schools and the process for a formalised treaty for Indigenous Victorians.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Coalition also promised to reinstate religious instruction classes in state schools, something removed from classes and made an opt-in process by Labor.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Arguably the most pressing issue of the campaign was public transport and infrastructure.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Melbourne's record population growth of more than 125,000 people a year made both party leaders focus on big transport initiatives.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Labor unveiled a $50 billion underground rail loop of the suburbs surrounding the city, though admitted the project would not be completed before 2050 and actually pledged $300 million for a business study.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Coalition instead proposed a $19 billion "European-style" regional rail network that would rebuild the entire network and include high-speed rail on four lines, travelling up to 200 km an hour.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Both parties agreed on the West Gate Tunnel, North East Link and Metro Rail projects, though the Coalition pledged to bring back the defunct East West Link project which was scrapped at a cost of $1 billion by the Labor Government.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Minor party the Greens sought to expand their numbers in parliament and make further gains in inner-city/suburban seats held by Labor such as Albert Park, Brunswick and Richmond.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The party proposed a dedicated bike "superlane" stretching 17 kilometres from Elsternwick railway station to Coburg, as well as further cycling routes connecting Box Hill and Richmond, Ringwood and Croydon and a connection from the Burwood Highway through to Knox and Deakin University.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Overall, most Greens policies were more closely aligned with Labor policies than the Coalition, a fact acknowledged by Greens leader Samantha Ratnam who said she would seek to negotiate with Labor to form government in the event of a hung parliament.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Labor leader Daniel Andrews reacted negatively to this possibility saying "no deal will be offered" and criticising the Greens for allegedly "refusing to call out denigration of women", in reference to past sexist comments made by the Greens candidate for the seat of Footscray, Angus McAlpine.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The total number of people who voted early in the last two weeks of the campaign was 1,639,202, which made up 40% of the eligible voting population.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] of voting intention from all opinion polling since the last election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] In the lead-up to the election, Poll aggregation site Poll Bludger placed the two-party-preferred vote for Labor at 53.5%, coupled with primary vote shares at 41.0% for Labor, 39.8% for the Liberal/National Coalition, and 11.1% for the Greens.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Election Analyst Antony Green stated on the ABC's election coverage that the result was "four to five percent better (for Labor) than all the opinion polls, which is the most out I've seen opinion polls in a long time in this country".
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The margin here is the Greens margin at the 2014 election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Labor's victory came primarily on the strength of a larger-than-expected swing in eastern Melbourne, which has historically decided elections in Victoria.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] According to the ABC's election analyst Antony Green, the swing, which exceeded both the statewide swing and the most optimistic projections, resulted in the eastern suburbs being swept up in a "band of red".
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] They also took a number of seats in areas considered Liberal heartland.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Hawthorn, for instance, fell to Labor for only the second time ever and for the first time in 63 years.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Bass elected a Labor member for the first time ever; the seat and its predecessors, Gippsland West and Westernport, had been in conservative hands for all but two terms since 1909.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Labor benefited from an enormous swing toward it and consequently picked up at least one seat in most regions, winning 18 seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The swing against the Coalition in the lower house was replicated in the Council and they lost five seats to finish with only 11.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Most of the minor parties were the beneficiaries of above-the-line voting, though Reason Party MP Fiona Patten was re-elected on the back of a strong below-the-line vote in Northern Metropolitan.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] The Greens were the biggest losers of the system, losing four of their five upper house members and only re-electing party leader Samantha Ratnam.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Derryn Hinch's Justice Party was the biggest winner on the crossbench, picking up three seats, however the party's member for Western Metropolitan (Catherine Cumming) defected to sit as an independent prior to being sworn in.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Michael O'Brien replaced Matthew Guy as Leader of the Opposition following Guy's resignation.
[src:animal-justice-party/2018-victorian-state-election] Victorian state Liberal President Michael Kroger resigned following the election result and the Liberals defeat.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The **2019 New South Wales state election** was held on Saturday 23 March 2019 to elect the 57th Parliament of New South Wales, including all 93 seats in the Legislative Assembly and 21 of the 42 seats in the Legislative Council.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The two-term incumbent Liberal/National Coalition Government led by Premier Gladys Berejiklian and Deputy Premier John Barilaro was re-elected to a third four-year term with a reduced majority in the Legislative Assembly, where government is formed.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The main Opposition Labor Party under Michael Daley won an increased share of the vote in most districts, though the party was unable to successfully gain support in key marginal electorates.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Minor parties the Greens and the Shooters, Fishers and Farmers Party, as well as several independent MPs, also contested the election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The Coalition won 48 seats (35 Liberal, 13 National), suffering a loss of four seats from the preceding election and providing the incumbent government with a slim three-seat majority.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The Labor Party won 36 seats, an increase of two seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor, and to a larger extent the Coalition, both suffered primary vote swings against them.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Minor parties the Greens and the Shooters, Fishers and Farmers each won three seats, and they were joined on the crossbench by three independents.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] In the Legislative Council, 21 seats were up for election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The Coalition won eight seats, Labor seven, the Greens and One Nation each picked up two seats, whilst the Shooters, Fishers and Farmers Party and Animal Justice Party claimed one seat each.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] One Nation's lead candidate Mark Latham, who led the Labor Party to defeat at the 2004 federal election, was elected to the Council.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] In total the Coalition held 17 seats, Labor 14 and crossbenchers of other parties held 11.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The result left the Berejiklian Government needing at least five votes to pass legislation, down from the two they needed in the previous Council.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] It was the first time that the Coalition won a third consecutive term in office in New South Wales since the 1971 state election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Berejiklian became the first woman to lead a party to a state election victory in New South Wales, as well as the third woman to lead a party to a victory at a state election in Australia (after Queensland's Anna Bligh and Annastacia Palaszczuk) and the first non-Labor woman to do so.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Daley had initially indicated that he would stay on as leader despite the loss.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] However, facing the prospect of a leadership spill, Daley announced several days after the election that he would stand down as leader and not contest a subsequent leadership election, to be held after the federal election in May.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Deputy leader Penny Sharpe served as interim leader of the party in the intervening period.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] That leadership election was subsequently held, and Strathfield MP Jodi McKay was elected as Labor Party Leader, against Kogarah MP Chris Minns.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] New South Wales has compulsory voting, with optional preferential voting in single-member seats for the lower house and single transferable vote with optional preferential above-the-line voting in the proportionally represented upper house.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] ABC election analyst Antony Green called the election for the Coalition at about 8:15pm, over two hours after the 6:00pm close of polling booths.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] However, it took a further two full days of official vote counting by the electoral commission before the ABC election computer was able to project that the Coalition had retained majority government.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Compared with results from 2015 election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] despite a very large swing, their 22.7-point margin in 2015 is used for swing calculations.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] lost by the Coalition since 2015 occurred from even larger swings, both won by two new crossbenchers.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] At the 2015 election, the Coalition retained government with a reduced majority of 54 seats from 69 seats in the 2011 election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] In the course of the previous parliamentary term, the Coalition had been reduced to 61 seats due to ICAC proceedings that resulted in the departure of eight MPs from the Liberal Party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The Labor Party gained 11 seats at the election, for a total of 34 seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The Greens gained a record three seats whilst independents Greg Piper and Alex Greenwich both retained their seats.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Several by-elections were held after the 2015 election.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] In most of these, the party holding the seat did not change.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] In the 2016 Orange by-election, Philip Donato of the Shooters, Fishers and Farmers Party won the seat, previously held by the Nationals.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] In the 2018 Wagga Wagga by-election, independent candidate Joe McGirr won the seat, previously held by the Liberal Party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The 2015 election saw the incumbent Liberal/National coalition gain one seat in the Legislative Council to have a total of 20 seats, despite a 5.1-point swing against them.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The Labor Party lost two seats, bringing their total down to 12; the Greens, Shooters and Fishers, and Christian Democrats saw no gains or losses in the election: these parties won five seats, two seats and two seats, respectively.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The only gain came from the Animal Justice Party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The Liberal Party campaign was launched by Premier Gladys Berejiklian on 10 March.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The event was attended by Prime Minister Scott Morrison, former Prime Minister John Howard, and former New South Wales Premiers Mike Baird, Barry O'Farrell, John Fahey, and Nick Greiner.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Berejiklian announced that, if re-elected, the government would spend $2 billion over four years to construct two new metro rail lines: one from the Sydney CBD to Parramatta and one from St Marys station to the planned Western Sydney Airport.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] She also pledged to build or upgrade 29 hospitals and clinics state-wide, including redevelopments of the Bankstown Lidcombe Hospital and John Hunter Hospital at a cost of $1.3 billion and $780 million, respectively.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Another $917 million was pledged for the construction of eight new schools and the upgrade of 31 others.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The Labor Party campaign was launched by Opposition Leader Michael Daley on 10 March.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The event was attended by federal Labor leader and Leader of the Opposition Bill Shorten, as well as former New South Wales Premiers Kristina Keneally, Bob Carr, and Barrie Unsworth.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor also committed to banning conversion therapy and decriminalisation of abortion and also to have abortion performed within public hospitals if elected.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] A $1 billion water fund was announced for the purpose of upgrading water infrastructure and protecting the water supply of regional communities, particularly in times of drought.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] On 19 March, a September 2018 video surfaced in which opposition leader Daley made negative comments about Asian immigration in Sydney: "Our young children will flee and who are they being replaced with?
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] They are being replaced by young people from typically Asia with PhDs...
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] So there's a transformation happening in Sydney now where our kids are moving out and foreigners are moving in and taking their jobs." Daley apologised for his comments, stating "What I was referring to was housing affordability in Sydney ...
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] I could've expressed myself better, no offence was meant." Despite the apology after the video's release the controversy dogged Mr Daley and Labor until the end of the campaign.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The video is suggested to have ultimately cost Labor potential victory in a number of key seats in Sydney with large proportions of voters from Asian backgrounds, and was also likely held back until it would be politically most beneficial to the incumbent government.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor's preference deals with the Shooters, Fishers and Farmers Party was criticised by Premier Berejiklian, who suggested that a Labor government supported by the Shooters could lead to looser gun laws.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Daley responded by pledging to resign from parliament if gun laws were changed, even if the measures were passed by the Coalition.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Berejiklian stated that the deal was not comparable as it only concerned the upper house, and would not affect government formation, which occurs in the lower house.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The incumbent Liberal government planned to continue with the demolition of the Sydney Football Stadium and, if re-elected, to replace it with a new $730 million venue.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The issue was thrust into the limelight by Peter FitzSimons, a local media figure, who remarked that he believed that the Government would not win the election unless they cancelled the stadium rebuild.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Michael Daley seized on the apparent popularity of the anti-stadium movement to call the election a "referendum on stadiums", as well as touring a "campaign bus" with the slogan "Schools & Hospitals Before Stadiums" on the side.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] In March, Labor unveiled its plan for a "war on waste", seeking to ban single-use plastic bags, phase out single-use plastic, and reduce waste and create jobs by investing $140 million in recycling initiatives.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Pauline Hanson's One Nation under the leadership of Mark Latham ran on a platform which opposed immigration, congestion, overdevelopment and renewable power, and proposed DNA tests for Aboriginal welfare recipients and banning the burqa in government buildings.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Daley proposed a plan to protect koalas and create a Great Koala National Park.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] He also vowed that a government led by Labor would invest in a new national park to comprise areas within south west Sydney.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The first debate of the campaign was held on 8 March on the ABC.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] It featured Premier Gladys Berejiklian and Opposition Leader Michael Daley, and was moderated by Brigid Glanville.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Subjects discussed included the demolition of the Sydney Football Stadium, cost of living in Sydney, transportation, infrastructure, and the Murray–Darling basin.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] In their final remarks, Berejiklian pledged to continue the current course and finish pending projects, while Daley emphasised his commitment to regional voters and promised assistance for dairy farmers.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] A second debate was held on 20 March on Sky News featuring Premier Gladys Berejiklian and Opposition Leader Michael Daley, moderated by David Speers.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] An audience of 100 undecided voters asked questions to the two leaders.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Issues discussed included stadium funding, climate change, domestic violence, TAFE funding, the M4 motorway toll.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] When questioned on Labor's planned TAFE funding increase, Daley struggled to provide a precise figure before openly blurting out a figure of $3 billion, which drew laughter from the audience and an immediate "No!" from the Premier.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Berejiklian was also unable to clarify whether motorists would be charged a toll to travel on the M4 from Parramatta to Penrith.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The audience were subsequently asked who they were more inclined to vote for after the debate.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] 50 favoured Berejiklian, while 25 favoured Daley; a further 25 were undecided.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] In February 2019, it was reported that Shooters, Fishers and Farmers Party and Pauline Hanson's One Nation sent preferences each other's way in the upper house.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Labor leader Michael Daley said the party's head office, instead of the leader's, would decide preference deals on a "seat-by-seat basis".
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] While refusing to rule out Labor dealing with the Shooters, Fishers and Farmers, Daley said Labor would not accept a preference deal with One Nation "because they are a racist party".
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The National Party made preference deals with the Liberal Democrats and Christian Democratic Party in the Legislative Council, suggesting that voters give them second and third preferences respectively.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] 18 parties were registered with the New South Wales Electoral Commission (NSWEC).
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] All eighteen parties nominated candidates for election to the Legislative Council.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The seat of Wollondilly was vacated following the resignation of Liberal MP Jai Rowell on 17 December 2018.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The parliament has fixed four-year terms with the election held on the fourth Saturday in March, though the Governor may dissolve the house sooner on the advice of the Premier.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The Sunday newspapers both endorsed the Liberal/National Party Coalition over the Labor Party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The *Sunday Telegraph* pointed out that despite having commenced many large scale infrastructure projects "the problem for the Government is that nothing is quite finished yet".
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] Despite this, it singled out the Labor Opposition for not having "done enough to atone for the sins of its recent history" of corruption.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] It called for stability of leadership after a decade of instability, recommending to voters that they "should give the Government the opportunity to see through the transformation of our state".
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] All four weekday newspapers endorsed the Liberal/National Party Coalition over the Labor Party.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The *Green Left Weekly* endorsed Socialist Alliance.
[src:animal-justice-party/2019-new-south-wales-state-election] The *Red Flag (newspaper)* endorsed voting for both Socialist Alliance and the Greens.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] The **Animal Justice Party** (**AJP**) is a political party in Australia founded in 2009 by Steve Garlick.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] The party was registered by the Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) on 3 May 2011.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] The party is also registered in New South Wales, Queensland, South Australia, Victoria, Western Australia, Tasmania, Northern Territory, and the Australian Capital Territory.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] The AJP is the first political party in Australia formed solely to advance animal welfare issues.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] It has 62 published policies under the categories "Animals", "Planet" and "People".
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] The party aims to give animals constitutional protection based on their sentience, as opposed to their instrumental value.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] The AJP opposes the export of any live animals for profit, especially slaughter.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] The AJP aims to legally recognise the inherent Rights of Nature.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] The party also opposes the eating of meat, and advocates a plant-based diet.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] Additionally, the AJP has 'positions' which are stances on human social issues that do not affect animals and which the AJP says flow clearly from its core values: Kindness, Equality, Rationality and Non-violence.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] The party advocates for the abolition of factory farming, greyhound racing and the live export trade.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] The party also advocates for the termination of government funding for all animal product industries and for the advertising of animal products to be banned.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] Banning live animal exports remains a core commitment on the AJP's election platform.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] At the 2015 New South Wales election, Mark Pearson gained 1.8% of the primary vote and won a seat in the New South Wales Legislative Council, giving the party its first parliamentary representation.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] At the 2019 New South Wales election the AJP increased its primary vote to 1.95% of the state total and winning a second seat filled by Emma Hurst MLC.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] The AJP won its first seat in the Victorian Legislative Council at the 2018 Victorian election elected Andy Meddick MLC.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] The AJP's second-ever Member of the Victorian Parliament, Georgie Purcell, was elected in 2022.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] The party also increased its primary vote over that of the 2014 Victorian election.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] Bruce Poon stood at the 2018 by-election for Lord Mayor of Melbourne achieving 1.63% of the vote.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] In 2020, the party's first ever local government representatives were elected: Charlie Vincent in the Alpine Shire and Julie Sloan in the City of Greater Bendigo.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] A 2021 qualitative study into the AJP interviewed members about the role of women in the party.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] In 2017, Animal Justice Party MP Mark Pearson was allegedly found to have eaten seafood at a Japanese restaurant located in Sydney.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] Pearson acknowledged that whilst he eats an "almost vegan" diet, he "strayed for that morsel [of fish]".
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] This incident resulted in backlash from the vegan community of Sydney, particularly on their Facebook pages, where they accused Pearson of being a "traitor" and a "hypocrite".
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] In response, Pearson asserted that "the main constituents of the party are not vegans or vegetarians" and that "We did not get elected by the vegan community." Since then, the AJP has introduced rules that leaders and candidates representing the party must be vegan.
[src:animal-justice-party/animal-justice-party] Notable vegan candidates include Chris Delforce, director of the documentary *Dominion*, and James Aspey.
